In C++ without resorting to templates or more advanced patterns, code duplication will often occur when dealing with similar classes that operate on different data types. However, there are other ways you can reduce the amount of duplicate code, such as using composition instead of inheritance, polymorphism, or simply accepting the duplication when it isn't harmful.

That said, your case is a good example of when using templates is actually quite justified, as they are the primary C++ language feature designed to handle this type of situation where the only difference between classes is the data type of their members.

But since you've mentioned wanting to avoid templates or complicated solutions, one approach you might consider is to use a single class that always works with the highest precision required (in this case, floats) and convert to int when necessary. Depending on your specific requirements for precision and performance, this may be an acceptable compromise.

Here's a modified version of your Point class that can be used for both integer and floating-point coordinates using method overloading:

```cpp
class Point {
public:
    // Generic constructor to handle both float and int initialization
    Point(float x, float y) : x_(x), y_(y) {}

    // Specialized constructor for initializing from integers
    Point(int x, int y) : x_(static_cast<float>(x)), y_(static_cast<float>(y)) {}

    // Getters can return as float or int
    float GetX() const { return x_; }
    int GetXInt() const { return static_cast<int>(x_); }

    float GetY() const { return y_; }
    int GetYInt() const { return static_cast<int>(y_); }

    // Setters can accept both float and int
    void SetX(float x) { x_ = x; }
    void SetX(int x) { x_ = static_cast<float>(x); }

    void SetY(float y) { y_ = y; }
    void SetY(int y) { y_ = static_cast<float>(y); }

    // Convert to SDL_Point or SDL_FPoint as needed
    SDL_Point ToSDLPoint() const {
        return { GetXInt(), GetYInt() };
    }

    SDL_FPoint ToSDLFPoint() const {
        return { GetX(), GetY() };
    }

private:
    float x_, y_; // Internal storage in highest required precision
};
```

In the above example, your single `Point` class can be used wherever `SDL_Point` or `SDL_FPoint` is expected. When you need to pass an `SDL_Point` to an SDL function, you can call `ToSDLPoint()` to get an integer-coordinates version, while `ToSDLFPoint()` is available if floating-point precision is required.

Of course, this approach might not be suitable if you absolutely must store integer coordinates without any floating-point rounding error for some part of your application. If you really need two separate classes but want to avoid templates, there's not much you can do to avoid duplicated code aside from keeping your classes as lean as possible and moving shared logic into helper functions if practical.

It seems like you're trying to provide a clear and consistent way for users of your Renderer class to draw lines or polylines, where a polyline is essentially a series of connected lines.

Here's what you can do to simplify your implementation:

1. **Single Method for Drawing**: Internally, you can have a single method to handle drawing both simple lines (with 2 points) and complex polylines (with more than 2 points). This method would take a list of points and draw lines between each consecutive pair of points.

2. **Public Interface for Convenience**: Externally, you can provide two public methods: `DrawLine` for drawing a single line segment and `DrawLines` (or `DrawPolyline`) for drawing multiple segments. This is just for convenience and clarity for the users of your Renderer class.

3. **Delegation**: The `DrawLine` method can simply construct a temporary list of points (just the start and end points) and delegate to the internal method that handles multiple points. If `DrawLines` is called with a `Line` object that contains only two points, it would effectively do the same thing; otherwise, it would pass the full list of points to the internal method.

Here's a pseudo-code example to illustrate the concept:

```cpp
class Renderer {
public:
    // Draws a single line segment
    void DrawLine(const Point& start, const Point& end) {
        std::vector<Point> points = {start, end};
        DrawPoints(points);
    }

    // Draws a polyline based on the given Line object
    void DrawLines(const Line& line) {
        DrawPoints(line.GetPoints());
    }

private:
    // Private method to handle the drawing, regardless of point count
    void DrawPoints(const std::vector<Point>& points) {
        if (points.size() < 2) return; // Need at least two points to draw a line

        // Iterate over the points and draw lines between each consecutive pair
        for (size_t i = 0; i < points.size() - 1; ++i) {
            // Internal SDL drawing function, using SDL primitive or your own
            InternalDrawLine(points[i], points[i + 1]);
        }
    }

    // Draw line between two points, internal function that interacts with SDL
    void InternalDrawLine(const Point& start, const Point& end) {
        // Implementation using SDL functions or your own rendering logic
        // For example: SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, start.GetX(), start.GetY(), end.GetX(), end.GetY());
    }
};

class Line {
public:
    // Method to provide access to the line's points
    const std::vector<Point>& GetPoints() const {
        return points;
    }

    // ... Other methods to manipulate the line ...

private:
    std::vector<Point> points;
};
```

By using this approach, you keep the Renderer interface simple and clear, while allowing for the flexibility that the Line class provides. Remember that internally, your drawing logic only needs to distinguish between a single segment and multiple segments. You can also optimize later if you find performance issues with temporary vector creation for single line segments, but often such micro-optimizations are unnecessary until proven to be a bottleneck via profiling.

