Yes and no. When you create the vector with `std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points(points.size());`, you're actually doing slightly more than just reserving space. You are creating a vector with `points.size()` default-initialized elements. This means the vector's size and capacity are already set to the number of points, and each element in the vector is an `SDL_Point` that has been default-initialized to `SDL_Point{0, 0}`.

Contrast this with `reserve`, which only allocates memory without constructing any elements. The size of the vector remains at 0 (no elements are considered to be in the vector), but it now has enough capacity to hold the number of elements you plan to add without reallocating.

Here's the difference:

```cpp
// This vector has points.size() default-initialized elements:
std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points(points.size());
// The vector's size is now points.size()

// This vector starts empty, but has room to grow:
std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points;
sdl_points.reserve(points.size());
// The vector's size is still 0
```

If you use `std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points(points.size());`, since the vector already has the correct number of elements, you would then need to overwrite them rather than using `push_back`. Typically, you would use indexing to set each element:

```cpp
std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points(points.size()); // vector is sized and filled with default-initialized SDL_Points.

for (size_t i = 0; i < points.size(); ++i) {
    sdl_points[i] = points[i].GetPoint();
}
```

However, if you initialize with `reserve`, you must use `push_back` or `emplace_back` because the size of the vector is still 0:

```cpp
std::vector<SDL_Point> sdl_points; // vector starts empty.
sdl_points.reserve(points.size()); // memory is allocated to fit the vectors but no elements are constructed.

for (const auto& point : points) {
    sdl_points.push_back(point.GetPoint());
}
```

The `reserve` approach is slightly more efficient because it avoids initializing the elements twice—once with the default constructor and once with the actual value. That being said, for trivially constructible types like `SDL_Point` (which is essentially a struct with two integers), the performance difference will likely be negligible, and you might prefer the clearer semantics of sizing the vector upfront.

